a. Remove a Directory
To remove an empty directory:

Bash
hdfs dfs -rmdir /user/practice
To remove a directory and everything inside it (recursive):

Bash
hdfs dfs -rm -r /user/practice
b. View/Read File Contents
To see the text inside a file without downloading it:

Bash
hdfs dfs -cat /user/practice/myfile.txt
Tip: If the file is huge, use -tail to see just the last kilobyte.

c. Download/Copy from HDFS to Local
To bring a file from the HDFS cluster down to your local Linux machine:

Bash
hdfs dfs -get /user/practice/myfile.txt /home/hp/Downloads/
You can also use -copyToLocal, which functions identically.

d. Copy/Move Files within HDFS
To copy a file from one HDFS folder to another:

Bash
hdfs dfs -cp /user/practice/file1.txt /user/backup/file1.txt
To move (rename) a file within HDFS:

Bash
hdfs dfs -mv /user/practice/file1.txt /user/practice/new_name.txt
e. Remove a File from HDFS
To delete a specific file:

Bash
hdfs dfs -rm /user/practice/myfile.txt
By default, this might move the file to a .Trash folder unless you have trash features disabled.

f. View File Permissions
To see the permissions, owner, and group of your files:

Bash
hdfs dfs -ls /user/practice


